Parliament rejects amendment to release Tymoshenko
The parliament of Ukraine has rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code in which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko is convicted.
The amendment would open the doors to the excarceration of the former prime minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing an agreement with Russia unfavorable to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet firm, the Court of Appeal has the obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there have been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code, which sentenced the former prime minister, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
226 votes were needed to be approved.
