IBM’s History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York 100 years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 – originally it was a brand used in Canadian and South American branches.
The foundation that led to the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies that date back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "check clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed IBM’s founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutting machines to cash.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, revenue doubled to $9 million and the company began to expand across continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost after forty years occupying the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pieces", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market under the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer comprehensive advisory and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned or the circumstances have improved, for example, in relation to transport and city administration.
For the trade sector, IBM introduced not long ago the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932 it opened a branch in then-Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates its strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague.Here is also a world-renowned research team that works with voice recognition.
