How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases travel only to the Socialist bloc, since trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the German Democratic Republic (DDR), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travel of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies offered in those times also trips to the West, but one had to catch up with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
But not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czech way of travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the DDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that the currently favourite destination, Croatia, could not be freely traveled until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European states, which caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not tired of trips to the West, everyone wanted to see them at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czech groups slept in the parks in camp shops, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food (conserves, bottles, etc.) with them to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in travel demand.
With the rise of travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 on, to regularly prepare travel using charter flight connections, which caused incredibly low travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on the volume of passengers.
By the late 1990s, Czechs traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries have started every year.This winter it will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they have spent more than 15 thousand Czech crowns per capita on travel abroad, including spending on the site of stay.
