Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy airing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a July Norwegian massacre that killed 77 people, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time that preceded his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t so hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report published on European digital populism by the British study centre DEMOS.
Bartlett says that Facebook’s personal information leak is so encyclopedic that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy – the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
By coming through Facebook, Bartlett and colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries — all without leaving the office.
“It’s an entirely new way of doing research,” says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in “Like”, wall messages and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a boost in research, boosting the number of academic papers with the site’s name on the title to almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to go through the game, and they’d never allow you access,” says Bartlett.
“Facebook removes all that – you go to them directly.”
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who spoke about their drunkenness feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drunkenness problems than students who remained silent about the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishes too many state updates with their drinks.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Institute for Childhood Research.
“We’ve found a way to identify children at risk that otherwise’t be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly “popping” its own population to obtain data.
The Site Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of election participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed – advocates of digital freedom have long argued that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
“I don’t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London’s Knowledge Laboratory, on a 2006 study he conducted with public Facebook walls of students.
“As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it’s impossible to know that part of a user’s profile information and wall messages are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” says Selwyn.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paper subject and a pen is still the best research tools that no one can use.
“There’s no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about the social – and a lot of the social still happens offline.”
