7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, Showing In A Theatre This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the technology genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been unleashed as a prequel to a series of special projections in the major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognised designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flow chart yonki – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time, it had been scarcely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This archival material, slightly re-released, is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, 68 minutes, which arrives on Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are large silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do well and bad, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining it all in detail here, it was and it did.
A quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of The Lost Interview:
How you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just how it’s done.’
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That is what I found.
Jobs brings to detail his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Confused by the way costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was made to the eye of a good man, and then adjusted with a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine commercial costs in detail.
The Jokes of the Pope:
Jobs tells the “Blue Box” he himself built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and screaming through the public phone and returning a minute later to the public phone from the next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both, we didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to talk to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two exploded in clashes just before the very Pope was awakened to go and answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone guide and made him a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute telephone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathod tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
He would make a trip to HP as a teenager and would waste time with that machine and write programs for her.
Improving the Innovation:
In several points of the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the march.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of base plates, he was asked by a customer if he could mount the entire equipment.
Working with just 30 credit days, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they shouted to me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
Large companies are losing strength:
Long before he led the rebirth of Apple, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble upon their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopies and printers, and what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company has no more success.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it’s this type of people who end up leading and people in charge of products are kicked out of the forum for decision making.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position dried up by the fault of people who do not have the notion of good products versus bad products - the knowledge of the necessary craft.
That’s what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
Innovation as an artistic expression:
“There is an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t do that the electrons do, the glass does them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain – these concepts – adjust them all at once...
At the end of the day, everything is reduced to taste—you try to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to what you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We’ve never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who casually were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, it might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dinner with health care law rivals while the court accepts the case
On the day that the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept President Obama’s challenge to the health care law, two of his magistrates, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were presented at a dinner sponsored by the lawyers’ firm that will present the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the revision petitions.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a cry of war for conservative activists across the country.
The magistrates agreed to admit the lawsuit to trial and, in fact, a historic allegation of 5 and a half hours is expected for March, and the outcome is likely to upset the 2012 presidential race even more, which will be at its height when the court’s decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be rejected will probably be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during George W. Bush’s administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles for many years.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner took place in a Washington hotel, hours after the court’s preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most important Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health care law.
Special guests at dinner? – Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
This is not in conflict with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal magistrates.
If they were not, it could be said that they would fall under Canon Code 4C, which says: “A judge can attend events to raise funds from law-related organizations and others, although the judge cannot be a speaker, an honorary guest, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia’s and Thomas’s absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive gap in ethics and indifference to the code goes against the demands of several magistrates that adhere to the court by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause (Common Cause).
“The judges were gifted in a gala fundraising with lawyers who have cases pending in court.”
Their appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in critics who say they mix court activity too easily with the agenda driven by groups like the Federalist Society.
Thomas’s wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, Conservatives argue that it is Magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as attorney general for the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pressured Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law to be impartial now.
