How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent titles shows us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment accusations with several women; each accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly hiding reports that said a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “picked” with an open microphone saying to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the ridicule with his denials quickly overthrown by the irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given exam answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
In any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That’s for sure, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill we should all acquire, for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” deception detection is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lies have been overthrown.
The liars look in the eyes.
They don’t always tartamude, balbucean, rub, or disturb.
It cannot be concluded either that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies", while women say more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than people who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a villain, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called “creating a base line.”
It helps to provide benchmarks for later measurement of changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
It’s better to know if someone normally hits his foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when you see his feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and non-verbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signs, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, bend toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview challenge” — that exaggerated breath of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions have ended.
Often interrogators falsely suggest that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the vocabulary of the subject.
Scott Peterson threw his leg to the bottom and used the time spent as he claimed his murdered wife was alive, launching a national search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman... Mrs. Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of “restrictive language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... to say truth... as far as I can... to my understanding.”
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will enhance anyone’s chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
