Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez’s management, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy.
The 2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-known as the change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development is registered.
February’s low temperatures, in addition to causing millionaire losses for the agricultural sector, limited the chances of the state’s economy to grow, caused a contraction of overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic 31.16 percent drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of ice impact, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares were damaged, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21,07 percent had partial damage, the main crops damaged were those of vegetables, corn and garbage.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate went to be 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in number of people throws more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase with respect to the first semester of 18 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out from public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Migration arrested
López Cervantes noted that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties to enter, and secondly because entering already have also many difficulties to find work, that people are staying and is demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the occupied population in the state works without being quoted as a worker before any social security institution.
Together with unemployment and informality, another of the state’s labor losses are low wages, the entity has the lowest remuneration in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of IED
Together with the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years is recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of the state IED totaled $630 thousand 697 which represents a drop of 87.74 percent from the $5 million 143 thousand 312 registered during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the State Government’s Secretariat for Economic Development accounts for a total investment of 17,280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In the face of the scenario of economic contraction, the government of the state requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, the same that would be destined the investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the purpose of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was for a sum of 2,600 million pesos, and until November have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, expressed that during 2011 it lacked the harmonization of wills of the various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, it failed to align the effort of all and above all the good march already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López stated that events such as the early frosts of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
“The low economic flow is the product of several events, including the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had,” he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he stated that it is necessary to incite the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
I work to do
The president of the Coparmex highlighted the importance of establishing a vision of the future that better encompasses the Government’s efforts.
“In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different subjects, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed,” he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in its way of conducting public policy.
“There are elements that allow to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done,” he said.
