Previous articleCorte validates “analogous shutdown” in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have raised against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogous shutdown" from 2021 to 2015, by not meeting the eight necessary votes to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers in issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to concrete the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the demand put forward by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said he did not agree with the arguments of the draft, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I do not consider that if I did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the rectorate of the State.
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and translates into a better utilization of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels.
To delay the change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, “exigent the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectorate of the State, encompassing a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the faculty of the State Executive.”
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, invades in some form the sphere of competence of the Congress, since the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative is being provided in the administrative sphere, he said.
Analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data cast by the PREP the difference between first and second place in the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total acts.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality as regards this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data thrown by the Program of Preliminary Electoral Results (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be remembered, Michoacán did not homologate its Political Constitution nor its Electoral Code of the State or its Law of Electoral Justice, since the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before concluding the legal deadline so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the time limits provided in the Law of the Official State Journal, with the argument that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the state president's vote on constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed around the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to carry out partial and total voting counts by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given in the event that: the results of the acts do not coincide; the acts of scrutiny and calculation do not exist in the case of the case or do not operate in the power of the president of the same; or when there are errors or obvious alterations of the acts.
In addition, the total counting of the votes received in all the boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the presumed winner of the election in question and the one who has obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that applied for the second of the indicated candidates.
The total counting of votes may also be carried out if, at the end of the ordinary counting, it is established that the difference between the allegedly winning candidate and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second-placed, in which case electoral packages that have been the subject of partial counting shall be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without accounting for the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
