The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take over.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well delineated,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the beaten confidence in Italy.
Underlining pressure on Monti to rush, market instability placed Italian bond yields at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti’s chances of success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are meant to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic-majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks added to pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday his consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a short breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti has said his government should last until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that he must be formed only by technicians, an indication of his concerns over a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have pointed out that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
