Going to Costa Rica is a dream made reality.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the band assures that for them it will also become a reality the dream of playing in the country.
This was stated by bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is on the South American wing of their two-decade-long celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make their only stage in Central America.
That day they will be performing at the National Stadium, from 7:30 p.m., alongside the angelina band The X and the nationalists of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcription is on The Nation on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican fans, it is a dream made reality that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream made reality for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’ll be able to stay a few days there.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What do you say to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even already refer to his concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really look forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are incredible.
My friends always went surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; so was how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Upon seeing the tour, they have come delivering huge shows with many songs.
What have they planned for their presentation in Costa Rica?
As we’ve never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is this due to?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have been not playing for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe what you’ve achieved?
Yes absolutely .
First, I think none of us imagined that we would be in a great rock band and having done so for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love and love to make music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Things could not be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the rise of the grunge?
It has always been an honour to be part of this big band.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s surprising when a move arises from a group of friends and it’s something uncommon.
From time to time, a band from a city arises, but it is much more strange when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with them all still and it’s an honor to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we are all lucky to be still alive and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give each one the freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you’re not too touring because it’s easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as one remembers that people are there for music, that reminds you that you have to respect the music and what brought it, without becoming acclaimed for being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really interests.
What do you remember about Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was something great.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think of the incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was a surprising human being and we wondered.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with various proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the letter of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That’s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing he thinks of.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
They are so many.
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it is no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think of it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s something wonderful because it’s music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is this change due to?
It’s interesting because I think there’s a couple of songs on the new album that may seem more lightweight, but there’s also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they can sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed touched them to me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think that when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and a family member or a friend is lost, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs undoubtedly represent that for me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
