Fujimori returns for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he has in his legs, his head doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who has been sentenced to 25 years in prison for violations of human rights committed during his reign (1990-2000), suffers from several illnesses, including a cancer in the tongue for which he has been operated four times and which remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told TV Channel N that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and the loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the indulgence for humanitarian reasons, however, said he did not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He has been operated four times of cancer to the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilograms to which other pathologies have been joined such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, arterial hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been detained since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people at the hands of a military annihilation squadron that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official committee, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with her Mexican partner, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans resident in Mexico, according to the agenda spread by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "appropriate for the exchange of information in everything that is political affairs between the two nations", according to the South American Presidency on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France arising when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country on a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's rejection and the call to consult its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20, a group of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has been in force with the South American country, since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has attempted in recent years to accelerate the creation of tax exchange agreements in order to leave the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), which consists of countries that have not implemented all international standards of tax cooperation.
On the trade level, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between both nations.
The bigotdo fontanero passes all three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
