Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transportation (SCT) that the results of the crash in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people died indicate that the helicopter impacted directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were the right to fly.
"The elements that appear to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the aspas had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that in the investigations carried out in the impact area, the appearance of pieces on the ground is not.
“In a search it is that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented in a structural way.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements for carrying passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary assured that it is a priority to get the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can take several months, could even reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, director general of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter operated at cruise speed and that this happened on soft ground.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of the impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
The visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during flight and on the ground.
The meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM placed suitable conditions for the take-off, as the aircraft advances to the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, layers of cloudiness were presented at low height.
Selected routes :
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew has sought a zone of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the latest record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideway trajectory.
The pattern of dispersal of the aircraft’s debris allows to assume that the helicopter hit the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion was detected.
On the site of the accident, there is still no evidence on the remains of the ship of some kind of explosion or fire.
The latest findings indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above the middle sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predicted to have disintegrated throughout the course.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After thorough searches in a wider area than the agreed site around the crash, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts a research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting a research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the Protocol 'Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center XXI Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN) Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav).
In the investigation is invited to participate the population whether or not right-speaking, go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to the minors, every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
He noted that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico Poniente State) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Mexico East State).
Once the goal of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day, the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays all participants are applied to anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (it is sought to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research obeyed the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was an increase in obesity of 77% in children and 47% in girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed,” said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population differs from others by its genetic history.
He that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent Indian American inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect whether they present some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood that he will suffer from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic ailments: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high calorie intake, that is, the increased consumption of sugary beverages, carbohydrates (tams, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high content in fats and proteins and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt of the UNAM would avoid bats
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals sent by the floor were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 beams each rainy season in the Mexico Valley Metropolitan Zone, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphalt floor is appropriate, the beams could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
In its conference A technological opinion of the beams, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, gave to know that the laboratory to its charge develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of beams.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalt, and others of low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents a solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, he added.
The above means that on the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt carpet, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abundantly, a last layer is placed called a rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with vehicle tyres, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt carpet and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires having the right thickness and the material of which it is made should be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil moistures, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult to leave, this causes a brushing of all layers of the floor and, therefore, the formation of bars.
In the process of forming a barrel, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed at the first signs with appropriate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of beams and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the flooring must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to prevent beams from forming frequently.
