However, according to experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not resulted in an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with non-competent persons or who had not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said on a teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
“Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal.”
“In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal,” says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, as they think it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that the fact of legalizing euthanasia will not mean that the lives of the elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for people who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that no trial should be initiated against them.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among their recommendations they suggest that it be indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of health care, if they have been legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The committee also calls for healthcare professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses assistance at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee asks that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and subjected to the same procedures.
Experts have expressed reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their concerns about the findings of the report of the experts of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts who sign the report "extreme", among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to patients in the terminal phase.
"This leaves the door open to a situation in which someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide," Deschamps said.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to prioritize personal autonomy over any other value of society.
Now, he adds, “in society, there are labels and limitations.”
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed her “strong opposition” to the report’s findings, which she called a “manifesto in favor of euthanasia.”
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, puts on trial especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
