Introduction of a "golden rule" budget in the Constitution
The government of the great social-democratic/Christian-democratic coalition that is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budgetary "golden rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure very higher than the maximum limit of 60% fixed by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency was reduced to a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay 3 billion euros more in interest each year,” said Vice-Chancer of Foreign Affairs Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the member countries of the euro zone on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of the public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government approaches the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease annually by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP annually, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The goal is that by 2020/2021 public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
