The Energy Policy:
Facts are more important than dogmas.
If there is one topic that can’t be addressed considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it’s energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of.
It is appropriate that an election meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, the demographic evolution will mean the doubling of electricity demand before 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing shortage of fossil resources will have to be reduced to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its power to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor for Switzerland, which aims only to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are determined to move forward with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is occasionally presented as an example, reality goes against such a discourse.
The Berlin election will result in an increase in electricity prices, increased energy dependence on increased imported gas, from Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the adverse effects will be noticed.
You should think about the case of Denmark.
Champion of Europe in the wind sector, from which he obtains 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy constitutes a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would restrain realism to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not oppose this type of energy in principle, according to surveys.
Remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widespreadly export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create unrelocalizable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of much of those SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer’s collapse is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our team, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scale, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between security authorities, French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is studied by all electric actors who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free way to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subjected to the policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with France’s self-proclaimed status of “country of human rights”.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the 23 May newspaper Libération) proclaiming in the past that France “needs no foreign talents, workers or waiters.”
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the orientation declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has close to two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was fixed by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fontaners.
On both sides, it is considered that immigrants are a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limits himself to include banality, indicating that co-development will allow solving the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is profitable electorally, but economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and undermines employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, low-skilled workers, by pressuring for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes of domestic workers and mainly exercise professions in sectors with lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
Positive effects on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the foregoing, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows implies a rise in long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in the European countries.
The International Labour Organization calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to the public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points he lacked "with his teeth."
Those teeth, which discouraged immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the coronels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and as directly as possible.
We know, from Napoleon "the Little", that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient by itself and can even become a “instrument of oppression,” as Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence has to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have currently shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and disorderly.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or an end to the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to strike out effects, but a common, full-right, quiet and continuous exercise of choices and democracy, this time at the European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we’t know where the list would end), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that plugs to the orders of the markets and of the rating agencies that suffers from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers a humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that the popular sovereignty regains the stepping stone of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having struggled for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But thinking of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by citizens, would be a new madness and would take us to a new dead spot.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to “make” Republicans.
Revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us become Europeans.
“Contactless” chip cards are becoming widespread
The world chip card show starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, the year 2011 should end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor cards (banking cards, SIM phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations from the cabinet Eurosmart.
The most powerful segment is the contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transportation or shopping simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
