From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front increases
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram.
The links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, suspected for a long time, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria’s Deputy Foreign Minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Algeria already “has the certainty.”
“The way the two organizations operate and the reports from the intelligence services show that they are cooperating,” he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two French citizens in Niger last January would have resumed the passageways.
Kidnapped in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their hijackers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the debris of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
The terrorist
The study of the calls made points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers captured especially the interest of the investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a northern Nigerian city, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a progress, but we must definitely wait for more formal evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
“But it is possible.”
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such “support” has become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or its operational modes, which now involve the use of suicide bombs or explosive devices increasingly complex and of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since pressured Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened people unworthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politizes and demands a strict respect for Sharia, while its militants fight against the wicked central government.
The latter are primarily oriented to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks on police offices multiplied.
Abuya’s reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern feuds.
Last Christmas, it claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would extend from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, disturbs all security experts.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somali al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
