Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
On Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will be delivered to Western Europe each year through a first 1.224-kilometer pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 that will allow for a total supply of 55,000 billion cubic meters of gas, that is enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already being talked about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land flow through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in making its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline constitutes a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," Fillon said at the pipeline's inauguration, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine pipe is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 meters of depth.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating from World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, for caution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Furthermore, measures for the protection of flora and fauna have been taken.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as much as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but the project managers abandoned it because the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to establish itself permanently in the sea off its coast.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of gas in less than a minute," said Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will thus be released into the atmosphere.
But the constructors consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have predicted joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a pure, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and at the output it is 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint company, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is favorable.
Gazprom subsequently leased the entire gas transmission capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of twenty-five years.
“Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom assumes the risk of the expenses alone.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the gas exit gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine is a brand booklet.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return people to the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine booklets with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook booklet.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The libretto is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a cotton blanket that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of booklet was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the twentieth century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far away has been the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, as the notebook attracts both businessmen, students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at its inception, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his books in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops of the city centre, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapes, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, tabs, pens, computer headsets... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week of Employment for Disabled People begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole population.
and discouraging?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for disabled employment.
“The progress achieved over the past 15 years is considerable.
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“H, there is still a lot to do.”
Unemployed people with disabilities still face numerous obstacles to access employment.
They tend to have a more advanced age: 37% are over 50 years old (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished their bachelor’s degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that especially hinder the return to the world of work and that “constitute the quid of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that surveyed directors have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities,” with an “excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities.”
The result: private companies with more than 20 employees are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of ... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“Now we reach around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, general manager of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The evidence: the number of establishments “submitted to this contribution”, as well as the amounts paid out, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their staff, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
